        "## 17.14 Feature importance and interpretation\n",
        "\n",
        "Feature importance can help explain a model, but it must be interpreted carefully.\n",
        "\n",
        "For a fitted random forest or gradient boosting model, impurity-based importance often favors continuous variables and correlated groups. Permutation importance is usually more meaningful: it measures the increase in error after randomly permuting a feature.\n",
        "\n",
        "For time-series features, correlated lag variables are common. If $Y_t,Y_{t-1},\\ldots,Y_{t-7}$ are highly correlated, importance may be distributed across them in unstable ways.\n",
        "\n",
        "A more stable strategy is to group features:\n",
        "\n",
        "- short lags: $Y_t,Y_{t-1},\\ldots,Y_{t-6}$;\n",
        "- seasonal lags: $Y_{t-7},Y_{t-14},\\ldots$;\n",
        "- rolling features;\n",
        "- Fourier/calendar features;\n",
        "- exogenous variables.\n",
