        "## 17.18 Common mistakes\n",
        "\n",
        "1. **Random train/test split.** This trains on future data and overstates performance.\n",
        "2. **Centered rolling features.** These use future values and leak information.\n",
        "3. **Using unknown future covariates.** Weather, prices, or economic variables may not be known at forecast time.\n",
        "4. **Forgetting baselines.** A complicated ML model should beat naive and seasonal naive forecasts.\n",
        "5. **Tuning on the test set.** Hyperparameters must be chosen using validation folds before final testing.\n",
        "6. **Confusing residuals with backtest errors.** A fitted residual is not the same as a genuine forecast error.\n",
        "7. **Ignoring horizon-specific behavior.** A model can be strong at horizon 1 and weak at horizon 14.\n",
        "8. **Overinterpreting feature importance.** Correlated lag features can make individual importance unstable.\n",
        "9. **Not matching strategy to deployment.** A direct model is not evaluated the same way as a recursive model.\n",
        "10. **Assuming ML handles nonstationarity automatically.** Feature design and validation still matter.\n",
